<HEADLINE>
<P>
TALES OF JAY LENO, MR. NICE GUY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I went to the Long Beach Grand Prix with only one intention -- to see Jay Leno, 
who was one of the celebrity drivers. As I peered through a fence, he came out 
of an outhouse. I yelled out, "Hey, Jay!" He turned and did his little "chin 
thing" . . . funny without even saying a word. 
</P>
<P>
OK -- so maybe it was a little rude to bother him at such a moment, but I sure 
wish that I'd had my camera! 
</P>
<P>
PAM LLOYD 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110589-0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 130141 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 5, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 107; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
171 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TALES OF JAY LENO, MR. NICE GUY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I enjoyed Lawrence Christon's Oct. 22 Jay Leno article, which brought to mind 
two incidents. 
</P>
<P>
I tried stand-up comedy at San Francisco's Holy City Zoo at a beginners' "open 
mike" night in 1976. The task didn't seem daunting until the comedian before me 
exploded with brilliant improvisation. He closed by inviting the audience for 
ice cream across Clement Street. This left mercifully few patrons to see me 
bomb. 
</P>
<P>
I asked the bartender if this comedian really was a beginner. His answer: "This 
was only Robin Williams' second time here." 
</P>
<P>
The bartender continued: "Why don't you come back next Sunday? You can go on 
before a fellow who wants to 'work out' here with some new material." 
</P>
<P>
The following Sunday, I dutifully performed and then sat slack-jawed along with 
other comedic hopefuls as we watched Jay Leno deliver a tremendous 1-hour, 
45-minute set. For him, it was just a practice. For us, it was an unforgettable 
lesson in humor, pacing, stage technique and reaching your audience. 
</P>
<P>
ANDREW TETON 
</P>
<P>
Santa Barbara 
</P>
</TEXT>
