<HEADLINE>
<P>
RADIO AND REVENUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding the Oct. 29 letters responding to Patrick Goldstein's Pop Eye column 
about KROQ-FM's format modification: None of the letter writers supported 
KROQ's change, accusing the management of selling out. But they are forgetting: 
Commercial radio is there to make money. 
</P>
<P>
If stations could run nothing but ads, most would. KROQ was losing listeners 
and thus ad revenue. Trip Reeb, the station's new manager, came from a highly 
rated modern rocker, 91X in San Diego, and his actions may well save KROQ from 
being forced to entirely change its format, as happened with KFAC-FM. 
</P>
<P>
As a modern rock music director, I appreciate the need for an outlet for 
underground/new music -- but the place for this is college radio. Stations like 
ours regularly play bands months or even years before they gain acceptance on 
commercial radio. 
</P>
<P>
KROQ must appeal to the majority of its listeners, and believe it or not, you 
alternative types do not make up all that large a demographic group. 
</P>
<P>
Face reality and just be glad KROQ did not decide to go more Top 40. 
</P>
<P>
RAYMOND SO 
</P>
<P>
Music Director 
</P>
<P>
KSCR, USC Student Radio 
</P>
</TEXT>
