<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK; 
</P>
<P>
10 TEEN-AGERS HELD IN PIN-JAB ATTACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ten girls arrested for allegedly jabbing 39 women in a series of attacks on the 
streets of Manhattan's Upper West Side told police the unprovoked strikes were 
staged "for fun." The girls, all black high school students aged 13 to 15, face 
charges of juvenile delinquency. Most of the victims were white women between 
the ages of 14 and 55, police said. Some victims had expressed concern that the 
weapons used in the attacks were hypodermic needles contaminated with the AIDS 
virus. But officials said the suspects told police they had pricked the women 
with ordinary pins. 
</P>
