<HEADLINE>
<P>
A PERSONAL HORROR STORY ON PESTICIDES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I feel compelled to respond to Supervisor Pete Schabarum's remarks to the 
Downey Rotary Club luncheon last Tuesday (Times, Oct. 26). Schabarum stated 
that "a couple of local politicians, desperately seeking some kind of issue to 
justify reelection, have jumped on the construction of a county facility and 
have repeatedly described it as some kind of chamber of horrors." Schabarum was 
referring to Norwalk Assemblyman Bob Epple and Downey Councilman Roy Paul. 
These gentlemen have tried to inform the citizens in the area adjacent to the 
pesticide warehouse of the potential dangers. 
</P>
<P>
"A chamber of horrors," if I may borrow from Schabarum, is an accurate 
description of the present warehouse in Pico Rivera. In January of 1987, my 
husband, a 14-year employee with the Los Angeles County Department of the 
Agricultural Commissioner, was exposed to aluminum phosphide gas. He and two 
other county employees were hospitalized for 24 hours. Aluminum phosphide is 
used to fumigate grain for the control of rodents, etc. The fumigation was not 
properly performed and the poisonous gas was vented into the interior of the 
warehouse. My husband and the other two men were in the warehouse attending to 
work-related responsibilities and were not involved in the ill-fated 
fumigation. After release from the hospital, all three were homebound for three 
weeks per doctor's orders. 
</P>
<P>
Schabarum stated that he "believes the facility will operate safely on Downey's 
western border with South Gate." I say to the supervisor, before any pesticides 
are stored, or any grain is treated, please see that the people directly 
involved with the daily function of this warehouse are properly trained. Also, 
in the event of any violation, the penalty should be in accordance with the 
penalties issued to private industry. 
</P>
<P>
MAUREEN HURLEY 
</P>
<P>
Norwalk 
</P>
</TEXT>
