<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: TALES OF THE DARK KNIGHT: BATMAN'S FIRST FIFTY YEARS: 
1939-1989 BY MARK COSTA VAZ(BALLANTINE: $17.95, ILLUSTRATED) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This big, elaborate volume traces the history of the Caped Crusader from his 
first appearance in issue No. 27 of Detective Comics through Tim Burton's hit 
film. "Batman" underwent numerous shifts in tone, graphic style and content 
over the decades: The earnest crime fighter of the early '40s bears little 
resemblance to the cynical, aging loner in Frank Miller's '80s graphic novels. 
Mark Vaz chronicles these transformations with the affection of a devoted fan, 
but offers little serious analysis or criticism. Lavishly illustrated with film 
and television stills, as well as comic-book pages and covers, "Tales of the 
Dark Knight" will delight comics fans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110589-0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 130534 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 5, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 20; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
102 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: AN ALPHABET FOR GOURMETS BY M. F .K. FISHER (NORTH POINT 
PRESS: $12.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A collection of short, pungent essays from 1949 that are less about food than 
people's attitudes toward food. M. F .K. Fisher reflects on great meals, 
terrible meals and the popular misconceptions of what constitutes good cooking. 
The few recipes she includes sound horribly fatty by today's cholesterol- and 
calorie-conscious standards, but Fisher probably would dismiss those qualms 
about fine food as unworthy caviling. The book's charm lies in her 
straightforward, delightfully self-assured style: At just over 200 pages, it's 
a minor gem that belongs in the library of anyone who likes to cook -- or eat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110589-0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 130541 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 5, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 1; Column 1; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
2901 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN ONE; 
</P>
<P>
TV NEWS: IS SEEING BELIEVING?; 
</P>
<P>
SIMULATIONS AND NEW TECHNOLOGY HAVE BROUGHT MAKE-BELIEVE TO NETWORK NEWS. BUT 
THEY MAY BLUR TV'S BEST ASSET -- REALITY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOMAS B. ROSENSTIEL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The woman on the train said she didn't hate Deborah Norville. She just felt bad 
for Jane. 
</P>
<P>
You know, Jane Pauley is so sensitive, she said, such a good mother. And, the 
woman said, she didn't really know Norville, Pauley's replacement on NBC's 
"Today" show, at least not yet. 
</P>
<P>
Her seatmate nodded understandingly. 
</P>
<P>
In truth, of course, the woman had confused television with reality. She had 
never met Pauley or Norville. 
</P>
<P>
But this intellectual sleight of hand is the central magic of television news. 
The images on the screen look real, and so people believe them to be real. That 
is why Americans say they have seen John Kennedy's funeral, the Challenger 
disaster or men walk on the moon. 
</P>
<P>
Today, however, many researchers believe television news is at a crossroad, 
technologically and journalistically. Increasingly, the TV images on which this 
trust is based can be manipulated -- or manufactured. 
</P>
<P>
And depending on the choices television makes today, viewers may soon conclude 
that seeing is no longer believing. 
</P>
<P>
Pressured by economics, and the success of so-called tabloid-TV shows featuring 
news re-creations, the three major networks are looking for new ways to tell 
stories, and increasingly the distinctions between entertainment and news are 
blurring -- particularly on a spate of new prime-time news magazines that use 
docudrama, news simulations and audience participation. 
</P>
<P>
At the same time, television news is acquiring new tools that make it easier to 
alter and create video images. One NBC news magazine regularly superimposes 
correspondents into scenes where they never actually were, using the same 
technology used to make Superman fly in the movies. 
</P>
<P>
And such technology is advancing rapidly. Last year engineers from Pixar in San 
Rafael, Calif., won an Academy Award for a short video starring a baby who was 
entirely generated by computer. 
</P>
<P>
"Fifteen years ago, I could not put on my newscast something that I had not 
heard or seen or recorded, unless it was something that an artist might have 
sketched," said Walter Porges, vice president of news practices at ABC. "Now I 
can create pictures and sounds to go with them that never happened. And that 
opens up all kinds of ethical moral problems for everybody." 
</P>
<P>
What are the implications of all this? The answers go well beyond whether it is 
journalistically responsible to simulate news. 
</P>
<P>
On the simplest level, substantial scientific evidence suggests that even if 
simulations are carefully labeled, viewers will remember them as real, 
confusing TV imagery with actual events. 
</P>
<P>
Some experts warn that Americans over time will come to see their primary 
medium for news, which currently has a high level of credibility, to be suspect 
-- hardly better than advertising. If so, TV news could be tampering with its 
greatest strength. 
</P>
<P>
Others think staged news and simulated images are part of a larger social 
change in which real events generally are being subsumed by synthetic ones. It 
has already occured, they say, in political campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
Nonsense, say those involved in the experimental programs. The good or evil of 
these techniques depends on their use. 
</P>
<P>
But all agree that simulated and altered news images are more than a fad, and 
television must begin to develop a new set of ethics to handle them -- much as 
medicine must wrestle with such technology as genetic engineering. 
</P>
<P>
Change in television news is nothing new. The medium is far different from when 
Douglas Edwards first read radio copy on camera for CBS. 
</P>
<P>
The most important difference, say news executives, is the march toward better 
pictures. Where once anchormen held up still photos on camera, now viewers get 
live video from anywhere in the world instantly. 
</P>
<P>
One result, some newscasters believe, has been the diminution of the 
journalist. Many say that while TV journalists like Dan Rather are certainly 
celebrities, today they are more narrators of pictures than authoritative 
figures interpreting unseen events. Who has the prestige of Walter Cronkite, 
whose on-air comments about Vietnam convinced President Lyndon B. Johnson that 
public support for the war was lost? 
</P>
<P>
"You are getting a lot more coverage and a lot less journalism, a lot more show 
and a lot less tell," said Lawrence Grossman, former president of NBC News. 
</P>
<P>
Even network executives like Robert Siegenthaler, president of Broadcast 
Operations and Engineering at ABC, worry that better visuals "have 
de-emphasized the words, and concomitantly the thought. . . . There is a fall 
off in the communication of understanding. The audience is in video overload," 
unable to retain all the pictures. 
</P>
<P>
If the move toward better pictures in the early 1980s was rooted in the 
improved technology of video and satellites, the current move toward new ways 
of telling stories is grounded in the declining economics of network 
television. 
</P>
<P>
As cable television and independent stations proliferated, offering more than 
just reruns, the networks saw their share of the prime-time audience shrivel 
from 92% in 1978-79 to 67% this year, Nielsen Media Research reports. The 
network oligarchy was dying. The old way of business was failing. And by 1986 
new owners had taken control at all three networks: Capital Cities 
Communication at ABC, General Electric at NBC and hotel magnate Lawrence Tisch 
at CBS. 
</P>
<P>
Their mandate was to cut costs and find new ways to attract audiences -- news 
suddenly was going to have to turn a profit. 
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Ronald Reagan Administration's deregulation of television 
eliminated one of the major purposes of the network news divisions, to provide 
public service broadcasting that would keep the Federal Communications 
Commission off their backs. 
</P>
<P>
The perfect model for news in this new world was CBS News' "60 Minutes." For, 
blessed with talent, an original format and a time slot pitting it against 
Sunday children's shows, it became a news show with entertainment-sized ratings 
in prime time -- and subsidized the rest of the news division. 
</P>
<P>
The allure was powerful. Prime-time magazines such as "60 Minutes" were more 
profitable because they were cheaper to produce and the networks owned them 
outright, while communications regulations mandated that most entertainment 
programs come from outside producers. 
</P>
<P>
ABC succeeded with "20-20." CBS tried to attract younger audiences with "West 
57th Street." And then came the rise of so-called "reality programming," or 
Tabloid TV, initially produced by non-network producers called syndicators. 
News-as-entertainment shows, such as "America's Most Wanted," "Unsolved 
Mysteries," "A Current Affair" and "Hard Copy," demonstrated that big audiences 
could be had by staging news-style dramatizations. 
</P>
<P>
Soon network entertainment divisions were producing such programs, too. And 
this year all three networks added new hourlong prime-time magazine news shows 
that borrow the techniques of entertainment. "Saturday Night With Connie Chung" 
on CBS and "Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow" on NBC both use actors in 
re-creations. "Prime Time Live" on ABC involves participation by a live studio 
audience. 
</P>
<P>
All three networks gave their producers more freedom to experiment with these 
prime-time formats, from the conviction, deeply held, that to succeed in prime 
time, newscasters must tell stories in new ways. 
</P>
<P>
But simulations are not the only innovations. Other techniques of entertainment 
programming in general are being mixed with news -- giving rise to 
"info-tainment," or what some have called TV's New Journalism, a reference to 
the blending of fiction and nonfiction writing techniques newspapers explored 
in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
"You cannot produce a prime-time TV program the way you do a Sunday morning 
(news magazine) program," said Sid Feders, executive producer of "Yesterday, 
Today and Tomorrow." "People want to be entertained more, they want their 
attention held more." 
</P>
<P>
And the search for new ways to tell stories is also a matter of technology. 
</P>
<P>
Feders' program regularly alters news images by superimposing correspondents on 
scenes, even if they never actually were there. The machine used, called the 
Ultimatte, mates two images so cleanly that the alteration is not detectable to 
the viewer. It even adds the correct shadows. 
</P>
<P>
Another machine, the Paint Box, allows producers to change the image's colors, 
to add or delete objects from the image, or to turn video images into sketches. 
</P>
<P>
Other machines can make objects spin, expand or shrink, add animation to video, 
change the focus, or obscure the faces of anonymous sources. 
</P>
<P>
And there is more to come. 
</P>
<P>
In laboratories and universities around the world, computer researchers are 
working on the science of simulating reality. 
</P>
<P>
"The state of the art now is we can simulate man-made things realistically," 
said Alvi Ray Smith, co-founder and executive vice president of Pixar, the San 
Rafael company that is one of the leaders in the field called computer-aided 
visualization. 
</P>
<P>
Images of buildings, furniture, machines and automobiles, moving and stationary 
-- anything made by humans -- can be simulated to the point that they are 
indistinguishable from reality. 
</P>
<P>
Simulating plant life is getting closer, researchers say. A company in France 
is starting to sell plant models on computer to architects. 
</P>
<P>
Simulated images of animals and humans are harder. 
</P>
<P>
Pixar made its first significant attempt this year by simulating a baby in "Tin 
Toy," the Oscar-winning video, which appears to be halfway between a cartoon 
and a photographic movie. 
</P>
<P>
But researchers say the technology is not yet there to simulate physiology. 
Pixar had to create 40 sets of muscles just for the baby's face. 
</P>
<P>
"The skin doesn't fold quite right," said Smith. "We still weren't close enough 
to reality to claim it was a real baby." 
</P>
<P>
The new technology has potential to improve television news, especially 
covering topics the medium once found difficult, such as science or economics. 
</P>
<P>
When a plane crashes, for instance, the Paint Box makes it possible to 
immediately create an animation from federal records of what happened. 
</P>
<P>
Proponents of the new techniques also argue that so-called reality programming 
is reaching audiences that otherwise would not watch news. "If you simulate 
socially significant things that otherwise people would be missing, you might 
be doing a service," said Doris A. Graber, professor of political science at 
the University of Illinois at Chicago and author of "Processing the News." 
</P>
<P>
Andrew Lack, executive producer of "Saturday Night with Connie Chung," said he 
is "much more concerned that all we show them (on the news) is Mexican bus 
crashes" than he is that networks are looking for new kinds of stories and 
formats. 
</P>
<P>
But the machines also carry obvious potential for deception. 
</P>
<P>
ABC News, for instance, used some of this technology when it staged a picture 
of someone playing the part of suspected spy Felix S. Bloch handing over a 
briefcase to a supposed Soviet agent. ABC technicians added a digital time code 
to the corner of the faked photograph to make it look more like a real 
surveillance photo. 
</P>
<P>
And, privately, television staffers admit other indiscretions. NBC News 
employees tell of one editor who regularly "sweetens" boring footage with bird 
sounds he has collected. That occasionally brings a letter from some astute 
birding enthusiast complaining of a bird heard singing in the wrong habitat. 
</P>
<P>
But potential transgressions could be much more serious. "If I were a budding 
dictator and I wanted to influence the minds of the people of the small island 
of X," Siegenthaler said, he could simulate television images "to make the 
current opposition leader look bad. If drinking were forbidden, I could make 
him look like he was coming out of a bar." 
</P>
<P>
Many critics, of course, have opposed all re-creations of news events. 
</P>
<P>
"You don't have to be a journalism school fuddy-duddy to wonder if CBS News 
hasn't invaded a realm from which it might better exclude itself," Washington 
Post TV critic Tom Shales wrote after the debut of Connie Chung's show. 
</P>
<P>
But perhaps seeing the issue as an ethical debate over simulations misses the 
point. This is more a matter of economics and technology. 
</P>
<P>
"It is like genetic engineering," Siegenthaler said. "You can tell the doctors 
not to mess with genetics, but, in point of fact, science marches on. 
</P>
<P>
"In the same way, the Ultimatte will be a cleaner clip, so more easily 
inserted, the Paint Box will get cleaner." 
</P>
<P>
What is needed, most argue, is a new set of rules for the new era of 
television. 
</P>
<P>
"Most of these tools are sort of neutral and it depends on their use," said ABC 
media critic Jeff Greenfield. 
</P>
<P>
"I suspect we will go through a whole period where we exploit this technology 
to the hilt, until we get to the point that we develop some proper standards," 
said Smith of Pixar. 
</P>
<P>
At this point, the ethics are sketchy. NBC News President Michael Gartner has 
issued rules that re-creations be restricted to prime-time magazine shows. They 
are not to appear on the nightly news. 
</P>
<P>
But former NBC correspondent Ken Bode asks: "Once you say you are no longer a 
virgin, what's the difference? What Gartner is doing is offering a lofty 
rationale for slipping standards." 
</P>
<P>
All three networks also assure audiences that any simulated, animated or 
re-created images will be carefully labeled. 
</P>
<P>
But some who have studied the impact of television believe that these new lines 
being drawn fail to account for how television actually works. 
</P>
<P>
Specifically, scientific research shows that people soon forget and confuse 
where they saw news. "We have known since the 1950s that source and message 
divorce over time," said Kathleen Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School of 
Communications at the University of Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, people tend to remember things as coming from more credible sources 
than they really did, in part because they don't like to think of themselves as 
manipulated. 
</P>
<P>
Hence, if people remember simulations, "it is a reasonably good guess" people 
will believe "they had seen the real McCoy," said Graber of the University of 
Illinois at Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
What's more, researchers believe that labeling simulations and issuing verbal 
warnings probably won't change that. Research shows that people process visual 
images separately and less critically than written or spoken information. 
</P>
<P>
The result, said Jamieson, is that "people believe what they see even if you 
put a notice up saying it's simulated." 
</P>
<P>
In the short term, "people will believe a lot of things that are not real," 
Jamieson said. 
</P>
<P>
And in the long term, some believe, television news could be tampering with its 
most precious power -- the sensation, clearly identified by research, that 
people believe television to be real. 
</P>
<P>
"People believe it because they think it is actually happening," said Shanto 
Iyengar, a professor of political science and communication at UCLA and 
co-author of "News that Matters." If info-tainment, simulations and simulated 
reality become commonplace, the effect would be to weaken "that exalted status" 
Iyengar said. 
</P>
<P>
"They are risking their credibility," Jamieson said of television news in 
general. "If you deceive the American audience, they ultimately will come to 
question news." 
</P>
<P>
Already, audiences make clear distinctions in the way they perceive different 
kinds of television, researchers said. They regard advertising with great 
skepticism, for instance, and view some kinds of news, such as foreign affairs, 
as more important and persuasive than others, such as celebrity interviews. 
</P>
<P>
But other researchers have less faith in the viewing audience and believe that 
the confusion over what is real will deepen. 
</P>
<P>
"Increasingly, Americans are going to be unable to tell the difference between 
reality and illusion," said Jack Solomon, a UCLA professor and author of "The 
Signs of Our Time," a study of semiotics, or social symbols. 
</P>
<P>
"We live in a commercial culture whose main job is to sell things. It is 
spilled out into politics and it is now spilling out into the news." 
</P>
<P>
And some see this debate over effects as overheated speculation. 
</P>
<P>
On one level, said Smith of Pixar, "the act of editing (videotape) is already a 
corruption of reality. . . . Once you are willing to rearrange time with 
editing, why not rearrange space a little bit." 
</P>
<P>
In the end, the debate in television news is not over simulating reality at 
all, but over values. 
</P>
<P>
Producer Feders is fond of quoting Bob Wright, the president of NBC. "He says 
you cannot set a table and then serve food that is so unappetizing that it 
drives them away." 
</P>
<P>
Don Hewitt, the respected executive producer of "60 Minutes," believes the 
decisive factor in TV news' future is not the journalists but the owners. He 
notes, for instance, that TV stations owned by major newspaper companies have 
helped popularize news re-creations by airing tabloid TV shows. 
</P>
<P>
And he was particularly upset, he said, when CBS' flagship station in New York, 
which is network owned, bumped "The CBS Evening News" from 7 p.m. to the 
lower-rated 6:30 p.m. time slot to make room for "USA Today on Television." 
When "USA Today" bombed, it substituted the tabloid TV show "Hard Copy." 
</P>
<P>
"If the pressure comes from the top, I think what will happen is the nature of 
the people who work in the business will change," Hewitt said. 
</P>
<P>
Even the vice president of standards at ABC, Porges, sounds uncertain at times: 
"I would hate to think I wasted 35 years trying to be right." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, ABC used simulation to report Felix S. Bloch spy case. Studies show 
viewers remember such re-creations as real, even if they are labeled. Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
