<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S., JAPAN REACH AIR ROUTE ACCORD; 'DRAMATIC EXPANSION' IN SERVICE SEEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner on Saturday announced a pact with 
Japan that he said marks the "most dramatic expansion in air service between 
the two countries" in 37 years. 
</P>
<P>
"It opens new vistas in terms of travel, trade and tourism," Skinner said late 
Saturday after the agreement had been signed in Tokyo. Transportation 
Department officials announced the "agreement in principle" in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
David Prosperi, assistant secretary for public affairs, said the pact could 
increase current air service between the United States and Japan by 25% to 30%. 
Six U.S. and three Japanese carriers currently fly routes between the two 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
The pact provides for more passenger and cargo service between the two 
countries, new all-cargo services and special services for Alaska, Guam and 
Saipan, Prosperi said. 
</P>
<P>
Prosperi said U.S. and Japanese officials initialed the agreement after six 
days of negotiations in Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
